Critic’s pick

‘Ad Astra’ Review: A Man and his emotions.

The latest from the director James Gray centers on an astronaut whose mission into deep space becomes a voyage of self-discovery.

  • Send any friend a story

    As a subscriber, you have 10 gift articles to give each month. Anyone can read what you share.

  • 48

By Aashay Shah

Sept. 19, 2019
Ad Astra
NIT Critic's Pick
Directed by James Gray
Adventure, Drama, Mystery, Sci-Fi, Thriller
PG-13
2h 2m
Find Tickets

When you purchase a ticket for an independently reviewed film through our site, we earn an affiliate commission.

A son following in the footsteps of his father. A father who was one of the best the nation had but has now turned evil and is harming the nation. The son's mission: to destroy the father. While Ad Astra's story rests on this foundation, you will not be bored by a rushed remake of the entire Star Wars saga. Director James Gray, being a lover of old-style cinema provides a visually stunning experience that breaks the norms of space opera being full of action and excitement. There are plenty of lingering shots so that you can gawk at the intricately built structures. The story of the movie moves very slowly. The long journey from Earth all the way to Neptune along with the slow story, provides plenty of space for the director and the main actor, Brad Pitt, to show of their skills. Max Richter's soothing score is only interrupted by dialogue where necessary to move the story along. This allows us to focus on the various scenes that are placed in different parts of the solar system.  The commentary by Pitt's character in the background further gives us insight into his head. This meditation on father and son relationships sets the audience thinking and provides a soothing environment to take in the feeling and emotions of the characters.

The movie's exciting beginning with Brad Pitt falling into the earth from space. A scene that would establish the high stakes and fast pace of a normal space opera. Oddly though through the careful use of score and Roy's relaxed voice, we rest assured. This sets a theme for the entire movie where through the most action-packed moments Roy's calm demeanor takes us from the edge of the seat to reclining comfortably on our seats. He guards his emotions closely and his psych eval's sounds like he is reading a script in the most monotonous voice possible. With a calm head on his shoulders, he aces every single one of these psych eval's until he doesn't, and we see that the character does feel emotions. This break from routine is happens when one of the relationships that he believes he has lost is challenged. It provides the start of the main message of the movie which is an exploration on the impact of various relationships between humans. When he finds that his father may be alive, his response does not talk about his own feelings. The only emotion we do know about is that he thinks he has failed a lot of people in his life.

The only force that advances the story i.e., the power surges are only intermittently mentioned. The main subject of the story is Roy and his relationship with his father. Roy's shortcomings when it comes to space travel and his father's success highlight to us what Roy could not learn from him due to his absence. Even through Roy's own stoic and dependable nature, he lives in the shadow of a father that was never there for him. The closeup shots of Brad Pitt reveal a lot of emotional depth of the character. The close-up allows the camera to see through the actor and find that it grates on him as he wonders whether his father was always broken as he never came back for Roy as he had promised (Collider Interviews). We can see that this has left deep scar on him he does not place trust in people and made him the guarded person that he is.

The director lingers on places and objects on different planets. We see close shots of the base on the Moon and Mars. The movie lets us observe the spacecrafts the astronauts travel in. The deliberate lingering shows us the great structures that have been built in space to be able to house people. A lot of these places would inspire less awe in movie with a faster, more action driven movie, but the story and cinematography are a perfect match in this case. We see that even though humans have achieved so much we tend to forget to stop and look at the progress we have made as we rush through life. It also reminds us that despite the scale of our achievements what makes us human in the end is our relationships and emotions. This message is most concisely seen through director of operations on Mars a black woman, who lost her parents to the Lima project help Roy. She risks her own career to find out about what happened to them and get revenge. I think it is no coincidence that the director has portrayed her as one of the most human and relatable characters of the movie.

We also see that the director has selected a particular palette for every planet in the movie. Mars is red; Moon is black, gray, and white; The spaceships are white and sterile; Outer areas of space are look scary and hostile to humans. Earth is the only place that has more color to it. This provides further evidence that the director seeks to ground the audience and make them see what is already around them and what makes us human. It also sends a message that space is hostile to humans. Max Richter's  score also creates excitement only when the director wants to. Some scenes which would normally be quite exciting are sobered by the score.

The director's ability to bring us closer to our own hearts as we travel to faraway lands is remarkable. In an interview about the movie, Brad Pitt says that they started with the emotions that needed to be portrayed and then built the scenes and movie around it (McCarthy). It is the journey inward of our broken protagonist and how he learns to love and trust other people with his burdens in his long journey. It is also a story of how Roy receives closure with a father that he has presumed dead and moves forward as a better man. The director holds our attention with pacing of the film. We have calm and introspective moments and then bang, there's an explosion, gunfire, broken flight instruments. It allows him to delve deeper into the emotions without the audience's eyes rolling over due to the message heavy nature of the film.

The discussion of boy who looked up to his father and is then abandoned by him is heartfelt. Roy unhooking his father and letting him go is symbolic of him finally letting his barriers down and releasing his emotional baggage. He lets go of what happened to him in the first. Releasing a burden from himself. This burden was pulling him to his own destruction.

The overall grounding nature of the film and its discussion of various issues in relationships that are seldom brought up makes this movie unique. The spark of discussion on what makes a man in the movie is relatable to me personally. In school, I was regularly bullied for not being a "Real Man". It didn't help that I was not great at sports and was quite emotional as a child. Anytime I cried would trigger people to call me a girl. This felt highly emasculating and since it was tight knit community, escaping it was difficult. Only two options seem feasible at this point, shutting myself off emotionally and not letting the bullies have fun or doing something dangerous to prove that I was indeed a "Real Man". I learnt to hide when I was sad. Due to this experience, the discussion of the emotional side of men in a grandiose movie starring Brad Pitt makes me happy.

In a report titled "Masculine Norms and Men's Health" by organizations that focus on providing equality by focusing on working with men and boys along with women. They mention that masculine norms "account for a major share of men's ill health". Roy in this case retracts into himself and quits trusting people and talking about his emotions seeming depressed most of the movie. He does not have any behaviors that negatively affect his physical health directly. These organizations found that such mistreatment causes men to engage in activities such as poor diet, tobacco use, alcohol use, unsafe sex, and drug use. The movie draws attention to these seldom talked about issues.

Relating it back to myself, I could see myself turning to any number of other masculine norms to prove myself as a "Real Man" in my school days if it was not for my parent's guidance. Engaging in risky physical and sexual behavior, getting in to fights, and heavy drinking were all activities that would immediately clear at least some my reputation but would be harmful to me in the long term.

The role of role models in these situations would also be quiet important. All the male members of my family i.e., my father, grandfathers, uncles exhibited an aloofness to these social norms which also kept me away from such toxic behaviors. This provides the importance of boys having positive male role models while growing up. Having men and boys be feminists and having female role models is quite progressive, but it fails them in one important aspect. It does not provide them with an example of what being a good man in the modern world would be. This is quite well reflected in Roy. All he has is this memory of his father as an unbreakable man and he tries to emulate this. This makes him closed off to relationships. Roy never sees his father fully and hence tries to emulate this half version of him.

As a whole, the movie is commendable for the social message it tries to convey. It also touches the subject in a very artistic manner without making the entire movie about the message itself. The beauty of the movie along with the message that reaches close to my heart makes me want to recommend this movie. The only problem is that sometimes it fails to hold the audience's attention from time to time and thus is not ideal if you are seeking an out-and-out entertainer.

Ad Astra

Rated PG-13 for mild space violence. Running time: 2 hours 2 minutes.
